{"id": "44968", "revid": "46519493", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=44968", "title": "Likelihood function", "text": "Function related to statistics and probability theory\nA likelihood function (often simply called the likelihood) measures how well a statistical model explains observed data by calculating the probability of seeing that data under different parameter values of the model. It is constructed from the joint probability distribution of the random variable that (presumably) generated the observations. When evaluated on the actual data points, it becomes a function solely of the model parameters.\nIn maximum likelihood estimation, the model parameter(s) or argument that maximizes the likelihood function serves as a point estimate for the unknown parameter, while the Fisher information (often approximated by the likelihood's Hessian matrix at the maximum) gives an indication of the estimate's precision.\nIn contrast, in Bayesian statistics, the estimate of interest is the converse of the likelihood, the so-called posterior probability of the parameter given the observed data, which is calculated via Bayes' rule.\nDefinition.\nThe likelihood function, parameterized by a (possibly multivariate) parameter formula_1, is usually defined differently for discrete and continuous probability distributions (a more general definition is discussed below). Given a probability density or mass function\nformula_2\nwhere formula_3 is a realization of the random variable formula_4, the likelihood function is\nformula_5\noften written\nformula_6\nIn other words, when formula_7 is viewed as a function of formula_3 with formula_1 fixed, it is a probability density function, and when viewed as a function of formula_1 with formula_3 fixed, it is a likelihood function. In the frequentist paradigm, the notation formula_7 is often avoided and instead formula_13 or formula_14 are used to indicate that formula_1 is regarded as a fixed unknown quantity rather than as a random variable being conditioned on. \nThe likelihood function does \"not\" specify the probability that formula_1 is the truth, given the observed sample formula_17. Such an interpretation is a common error, with potentially disastrous consequences (see prosecutor's fallacy).\nDiscrete probability distribution.\nLet formula_4 be a discrete random variable with probability mass function formula_19 depending on a parameter formula_1. Then the function\nformula_21\nconsidered as a function of formula_1, is the \"likelihood function\", given the outcome formula_3 of the random variable formula_4. Sometimes the probability of \"the value formula_3 of formula_4 for the parameter value formula_1\" is written as \"P\"(\"X\" \n \"x\" | \"\u03b8\") or \"P\"(\"X\" \n \"x\"; \"\u03b8\"). The likelihood is the probability that a particular outcome formula_3 is observed when the true value of the parameter is formula_1, equivalent to the probability mass on formula_3; it is \"not\" a probability density over the parameter formula_1. The likelihood, formula_32, should not be confused with formula_33, which is the posterior probability of formula_1 given the data formula_3.\nExample.\nConsider a simple statistical model of a coin flip: a single parameter formula_36 that expresses the \"fairness\" of the coin. The parameter is the probability that a coin lands heads up (\"H\") when tossed. formula_36 can take on any value within the range 0.0 to 1.0. For a perfectly fair coin, formula_38.\nImagine flipping a fair coin twice, and observing two heads in two tosses (\"HH\"). Assuming that each successive coin flip is i.i.d., then the probability of observing HH is\nformula_39\nEquivalently, the likelihood of observing \"HH\" assuming formula_38 is\nformula_41\nThis is not the same as saying that formula_42, a conclusion which could only be reached via Bayes' theorem given knowledge about the marginal probabilities formula_43 and formula_44.\nNow suppose that the coin is not a fair coin,