{"id": "45022", "revid": "36518604", "url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki?curid=45022", "title": "Natural transformation", "text": "Central object of study in category theoryIn category theory, a branch of mathematics, a natural transformation provides a way of transforming one functor into another while respecting the internal structure (i.e., the composition of morphisms) of the categories involved. Hence, a natural transformation can be considered to be a \"morphism of functors\". Informally, the notion of a natural transformation states that a particular map between functors can be done consistently over an entire category.\nIndeed, this intuition can be formalized to define so-called functor categories. Natural transformations are, after categories and functors, one of the most fundamental notions of category theory and consequently appear in the majority of its applications.\nDefinition.\nIf formula_1 and formula_2 are functors between the categories formula_3 and formula_4 (both from formula_3 to formula_6), then a natural transformation formula_7 from formula_1 to formula_2 is a family of morphisms formula_10, where formula_11. The morphism formula_12 is called \"the component of formula_7 at formula_14\" or \"the formula_14 component of formula_16.\" The components of formula_7 are such that for every morphism formula_18 in formula_3 we have formula_20\nThis equation can be conveniently expressed by the following commutative diagram:\nIf both formula_1 and formula_2 are contravariant, the vertical arrows in the right diagram are reversed. If formula_7 is a natural transformation from formula_1 to formula_25, we also write formula_26 or formula_27. This is also expressed by saying the family of morphisms formula_28 is natural in formula_14.\nIf, for every object formula_30 in formula_31, the morphism formula_12 is an isomorphism in formula_4, then formula_7 is said to be a &lt;templatestyles src=\"Template:Visible anchor/styles.css\" /&gt;natural isomorphis